Exercise: My proposal Recall that  egin{equation} 	\|u\|_p 	:=  \left( \sum\limits_{j \in \mathbb{Z}} | u_{j} |^{p} ight)^{1/p},  	\,\,\,  	j \in \mathbb{Z},  	 orall u = \left( u_{j} ight) \in l_{p}, 	\,   	u_{j} 
eq 0  	\, 	ext{ if } 1 \leq p < \infty, \end{equation} Let $u \in l^{p}(\mathbb{Z})$, $V \subset l^{p}(\mathbb{Z})$, and let $\{v_{j}\}_{j}$ be a sequence in $V$ which converges to $u$. The countable union of closed set is closed in $\mathbb{Z}$ when $u_{j} 
eq 0$. (unsure about this step!) Because $V$ has finite dimension, we have a basis $\{ u_{1}, ..., u_{k} \}$ of $V$. Also, $u \in$ Span$(u_{1}, ..., u_{k}, u)$. But, we have that $V$ is closed in Span$(u_{1}, ..., u_{k}, u)$ with $v_{n} 	o u$, and then $u \in V. \square$ Svetoslav's answer rewritten Recall that $$ V=\left\{u\in l^p(\mathbb Z): \left\{j\in\mathbb Z:u_j
eq 0ight\} 	ext{is finite}ight\}\subset l^p(\mathbb Z)$$ where  $$\|u\|_p 	:=  \left( \sum\limits_{j \in \mathbb{Z}} | u_{j} |^{p} ight)^{1/p},  	\,\,\,  	 orall \,u = \left\{ u_{j} ight\}_{j\in\mathbb Z} \in l_{p},\,\, 1 \leq p < \infty. $$ Let an element be $u \in l^{p}(\mathbb{Z})$, and a sequence of elements $(v^{j})_{j=1}^{\infty}\subset V$.  The series   egin{equation*} ||u||_{p}^{p} = \sum\limits_{j \in \mathbb{Z}} |u_{j}|^{p} < \infty, \end{equation*} is (absolutely) convergent which implies that its tail tends to zero. Indeed,  let $S_n := \sum\limits_{j\in\mathbb Z,j\leq |n|} |u_{j}|^{p}$ be the partial sums of the series and let $A=\sum\limits_{j \in \mathbb{Z}} |u_{j}|^{p} < \infty$ be its sum.  By the definition for convergent series, given $\epsilon >0$, there exists $N\in\mathbb N$ such that for all $n>N$ we have   egin{equation*} |\sum_{ |j| > n } |u_{j}|^{p} |=|A-S_n| < \epsilon.    \end{equation*} implying $\sum_{ |j| > n } |u_{j}|^{p} 	o 0$, when $n 	o \infty$.  Take for approximating sequence $\{ v^{j} \}_{j=1}^{\infty} \subset V$:   egin{equation*} v^{j} = (0,0, ..., 0, u_{-j}, u_{-j+1}, ..., u_{-1}, u_{0}, u_{1}, ..., u_{j-1}, u_{j}, 0, 0, ...) \in V  \end{equation*} and see that this sequence converges to $u$, i.e  egin{equation*} || v^{j} - u ||_{p}=\sum_{ |k| > j } |u_{k}|^{p} 	o 0 \, 	ext{ when } \, j 	o \infty.  \end{equation*} Therefore $V$ is a dense subspace of $l^{p}(\mathbb{Z})$ for $1 \leq p < \infty. \square$ How can you show better that V is a dense subspace of $l^{p}(\mathbb{Z})$?

